**Fixed Code:**
```go
package main
import (
    "net/http"
    "github.com/rs/cors"
)

func main() {
    // FIXED: Explicit domain mapping
    mux := http.NewServeMux()
    c := cors.New(cors.Options{
        AllowedOrigins: []string{"https://app.mysite.com"},
        AllowCredentials: true,
    })
    handler := c.Handler(mux)
    http.ListenAndServe(":8080", handler)
}
```

**Why This Fix Works:**
Restricting permitted origins to specific domains protects credentials (like cookies) from cross-site theft.

Directory Traversal (Path Traversal) allows an attacker to read arbitrary files on the server running the application. This can include application code, database credentials, or system files.

### Vulnerability Scenario:
```javascript
// VULNERABLE
app.get('/view', (req, res) => {
    const filename = req.query.file;
    res.sendFile('/var/www/uploads/' + filename);
});
```
The attacker requests: `/view?file=../../../../etc/passwd`

### Secure Mitigation in Node.js:
Verify that the resolved path stays within the intended directory.
```javascript
const path = require('path');

app.get('/view', (req, res) => {
    const safeDir = '/var/www/uploads/';
    const filename = req.query.file;

    // Resolve absolute path
    const resolvedPath = path.resolve(safeDir, filename);

    // Check if path starts with the base uploads folder
    if (resolvedPath.startsWith(safeDir)) {
        res.sendFile(resolvedPath);
    } else {
        res.status(403).send("Access Denied");
    }
});
```

