**Vulnerability:** Path Traversal via File System
**Severity:** HIGH
**Detail:** Reading files using raw concatenated user parameters enables directory traversal.

**Vulnerable Code:**
```java
import java.io.File;
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest;

public class FileServlet {
    public File getFile(HttpServletRequest req) {
        String filename = req.getParameter("file");
        // VULNERABLE: Directory traversal possible
        return new File("/var/app/files", filename);
    }
}
```

**Fixed Code:**
```java
import java.io.File;
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest;

public class FileServlet {
    public File getFile(HttpServletRequest req) throws Exception {
        String filename = req.getParameter("file");
        File baseDir = new File("/var/app/files");
        File file = new File(baseDir, filename);

        // FIXED: Verify path resolution bounds
        String canonicalPath = file.getCanonicalPath();
        String baseCanonicalPath = baseDir.getCanonicalPath();

        if (canonicalPath.startsWith(baseCanonicalPath)) {
            return file;
        } else {
            throw new SecurityException("Access denied");
        }
    }
}
```

**Why This Fix Works:**
Verifying `getCanonicalPath()` properties prevents path manipulation techniques using characters like `/../` by resolving absolute targets first.

